{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17723"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17723","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17723"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10437"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116747"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10437","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10437"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17723"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98734"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10161"},{"type":"tags","id":"10162"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24376"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24481"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116747"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMelanin production in the skin is regulated by complex signalling pathways that determine pigmentation patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal physiological regulation of melanin production?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Keratinocytes are the primary source of melanin","Melanocytes produce only one type of melanin","Ultraviolet light directly breaks down melanin","Vitamin D inhibits melanin synthesis","Melanocortin-1 receptor activation increases eumelanin production"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMelanin production is a key physiological process for skin and hair pigmentation, providing protection against ultraviolet radiation. This process is primarily regulated by the activity of melanocytes, which synthesise melanin and transfer it to surrounding keratinocytes. The type and amount of melanin produced are controlled by complex signalling pathways, with the melanocortin-1 receptor playing a central role. \u003Cstrong\u003EMelanocortin-1 receptor activation increases eumelanin production\u003C/strong\u003E through a signalling cascade initiated by melanocyte stimulating hormone binding. This leads to increased activity of tyrosinase, the rate-limiting enzyme in melanin synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKeratinocytes receive and store melanin from melanocytes but do not produce it themselves. Melanocytes are capable of synthesising two types of melanin: the brown-black pigment eumelanin and the red-yellow pigment pheomelanin. Rather than breaking down melanin, ultraviolet light stimulates its production as a protective response. Vitamin D production and melanin synthesis are separate processes that both occur in response to ultraviolet exposure; there is no direct inhibitory relationship.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe balance between eumelanin and pheomelanin production is determined by melanocortin-1 receptor activity and influences skin and hair colour. Increased receptor activation favours eumelanin production, resulting in darker pigmentation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Melanocortin-1 receptor activation by melanocyte stimulating hormone leads to increased melanin production in melanocytes.","Eumelanin is the dark brown-black pigment while pheomelanin is the red-yellow pigment produced by melanocytes.","The ratio of eumelanin to pheomelanin determines skin and hair colour."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora GJ, Mellifont R, Derrickson B, Burkett B, Peoples G, D D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition. 2nd ed. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98734"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17723"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98734"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-30T14:56:48+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-30T14:57:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10437"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116747"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"